  "prompt": "Why aren't most Canadian films successful but most Australian films are?",
  "response": "This is an interesting observation, but it's not entirely accurate. Both Canadian and Australian film industries face challenges, but there are some differences:\n\nCanadian Film Industry:\n- Smaller domestic market\n- Heavily influenced by US film industry\n- More focus on documentary and independent films\n- Less government funding compared to Australia\n- Often co-productions with international partners\n\nAustralian Film Industry:\n- Strong government support through funding bodies\n- More distinctive national film style\n- More international recognition\n- Smaller population but stronger film culture\n- More investment in promoting local films\n\nWhile some Canadian films have been successful (like \"Bon Cop, Bad Cop\" or \"The Sweet Hereafter\"), and some Australian films struggle, the generalization isn't entirely true. Both industries have produced critically acclaimed and commercially successful films.\n\nFactors contributing to Australia's relatively stronger film industry include:\n- More consistent government funding\n- Strong film school programs\n- More developed film culture\n- More emphasis on unique storytelling\n\nCanadian films often get overshadowed by Hollywood productions due to geographical proximity and cultural similarities with the US.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these points?",
